<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-170-248 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 674 937</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 29 1991 v25 n17 p112(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PC dealer competition creates buyer's market. (personal computers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brandel, William.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Slowed growth in the microcomputer market is responsible forimproved prices and increased service offerings from microcomputerdealers.andP;  Because all IBM-compatible computers are basically thesame, price is the only way to differentiate them one fromanother.andP;  Many corporate customers feel little loyalty to a dealerwhose prices are high.andP;  Attractive service arrangements areanother way for dealers to stand out in the crowd.andP;  Previously,dealers had reputations for low prices or good technical support,but never both.andP;  Now customers are able to get both from the samesource.andP;  The dealer's goal is to achieve some margin throughadded-value options.andP;  Even mail order businesses are beginning tooffer service arrangements.andP;  The way dealers operate is expectedto change soon.andP;  Dealers are either acquiring competitors orthemselves being acquired.andP;  Superstores will fade and accountcalls from salespeople will return.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer industryIndustry AnalysisMicrocomputersDealers and AgentsCompetitionMarketing Strategy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>